        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">DRC and M23 rebels engage in peace talks</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;"><strong>Summary: The DRC and M23 rebels have resumed peace talks in Qatar</strong></p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">The government of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) and the M23 rebels are back in <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-07-04-2025-h3-6-peace-talks" target="_blank">peace talks</a> in Qatar. This comes after days of unrest in eastern Congo. The first round of negotiations in late March was called ‚Äúpositive.‚Äù Following the agreement, the rebels have withdrawn from Walikale, a key mining town.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">The next round of negotiations is set for Wednesday in Doha, with Qatar mediating. The conflict in the region is complex. It stems from historical issues that began with the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-07-04-2025-h3-7-1994-rwandan-genocide" target="_blank">1994 Rwandan genocide</a> and the struggle for the DRC‚Äôs rich mineral resources, like cobalt and lithium.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">The M23, a Tutsi-led rebel group, has been one of the most potent forces in the region since its formation in 2012. While Rwanda has been accused of <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-07-04-2025-h3-8-supporting-the-m23" target="_blank">supporting the M23</a>, it has denied these assertions. The ongoing unrest has also drawn in neighboring countries, with Uganda and Burundi sending troops into Congo.</p>
        </mj-text>
    </mj-section>
