          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important"> How were the reciprocal tariffs calculated? 
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/trump-us-tariff-calculation-formula-trade-imbalance-infographic.png" alt="Infographic explaining the Trump Administration‚Äôs formula for calculating new US tariffs based on trade imbalances" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>Infographic explaining the Trump Administration‚Äôs formula for calculating US tariffs based on trade imbalances. Credits: CNBC</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Many people have misconceptions and questions about how the tariffs were calculated for specific countries. Trump administration <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-07-04-2025-f1-11-a-formula-is-used" target="_blank">used a formula</a> to arrive at the particular tariffs.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">To simplify, the US took its trade deficit with each country, divided it by total imports, and further divided it by two. For example, the US tends to shop more goods from China than to sell to them. The supposed trade deficit is $295B, and the total amount of goods imported is $440B.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">So, 295 divided by 440 will give you 67%. Dividing it by 2 and rounding it up gives us 34%. Each country‚Äôs tariff valuation was based on this formula. However, critics claim that this <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-07-04-2025-f1-12-formula-has-a-flaw" target="_blank">formula has a flaw</a>.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">According to senior fellows Kevin Corinth and Stan Veuger of the American Enterprise Institute, the formula relies on a flawed assumption: it assumes the elasticity of import duties with respect to tariffs is 0.25 (for every 1% increase in tariffs, revenues collected from those tariffs increase by 0.25%), whereas it should be closer to 0.945. Economists claim that if the formula were adjusted, no country would have more than 14% tariffs.</p>
        </mj-text>
